{
  "texts": [
    "Prior work has shown that neural embedding spaces can encode semantic relations as approximately linear directions, with relation-specific vector offsets supporting vector-style reasoning in the embedding space [14].",
    "In our framework, motifs are represented as interpretable directions in embedding space, and these motif vectors can be directly used to score new sequences, identifying regions that align strongly with a given motif concept.",
    "Stage II: Motif Localization via Concept AlignmentWindow-Level Embedding Extraction.",
    "To detect and localize functional motifs within proteins, we embed short windows of subsequences (Figure 1C).Formally, every window of length w beginning at position t is fed to the pretrained model as a standalone sequence, S t:t+w.The window size w is motif-specific: for each Pfam family, we compute the median annotated length from the training data and add a small buffer to account for natural variation across homologs.",
    "This yields motif-appropriate receptive fields without excessively enlarging the search space."
  ]
}